                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d142">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Press Release Issued by the White House on September 13,
                        1940</hi>
                    <note n="19" type="source" xml:id="d142fn19">Reprinted from Department of State,
                            <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, September 14, 1940 (vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, No. 64), p. 213.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1940-09-13">September 13, 1940</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>In order to further strengthen the national defense, the President, acting upon a
                    recommendation of Col. R. L. Maxwell, the Administrator of Export Control, has
                    issued a proclamation dated September 12, 1940, subjecting the following
                    additional materials to license requirements for export from the United States:
                    Equipment used for the production of aviation motor fuel and tetraethyl lead or
                        [<hi rend="italic">and</hi>] any plans or specifications useful in the
                    design, construction, or operation of such equipment or in connection with such
                    processes; plans, specifications, and descriptive or technical information of
                    any kind setting forth the design or construction of aircraft or aircraft
                    engines.</p>
                <p>These items are in addition to those announced in a previous proclamation by the
                    President, dated July 26, 1940, placing petroleum products, tetraethyl lead, and
                    iron and steel scrap under license requirements for exportation.</p>
                <p>The President’s proclamation of May 1, 1937, requires that exports of aircraft
                    and aircraft engines be licensed. The present proclamation, <pb facs="0288"
                        n="222" xml:id="pg_222"/> taken with the preceding ones mentioned, has the
                    effect of putting under the control of the President for export purposes not
                    only the aircraft and engines but also the plans and designs for building
                    them.</p>
            </div>
